    <h2 class="font-bold text-center text-xl md:text-3xl lg:text-4xl text-violet-400 mt-32 mb-8">Low Vision</h2>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">People with low vision can still see, but their vision is highly reduced even with corrective lenses. The term "low vision" encompasses a wide range of conditions, each with its own degree of vision loss. People with low vision often can't see well enough to drive or clearly discern details without enlarging text and images. Here are just a few types of low vision: </p>

    <ul class="list-disc text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8 ml-8">
        <li class="mb-4">Blur</li>
        <li class="mb-4">Blur with low contrast</li>
        <li class="mb-4">Cataracts</li>
        <li class="mb-4">Diabetic Retinopathy</li>
        <li class="mb-4">Hemianopia</li>
        <li class="mb-4">Macular Degeneration</li>
        <li class="mb-4">Retinal Detachment</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-center text-xl md:text-xl lg:text-3xl text-violet-400 mt-8 mb-8">Challenges & Solutions for People with Low Vision</h3>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">For people with low vision, reading small text on web pages can be a big challenge. People with low vision use screen magnifiers like ZoomText to enhance portions of the screen for better readability. People with low vision also use screen readers, as hearing the words can make reading small text easier.</p>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">Colors can also present a challenge for people with low vision, so it's important to choose color combinations with enough contrast so that its easily readable. It's crucial to avoid using color alone to convey information since people customize colors based on what's best for them.</p>

