    <h2 class="font-bold text-center text-xl md:text-3xl lg:text-4xl text-violet-400 mt-32 mb-8">Color-Blindness</h2>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">Color-Blindness refers to the inability to distinguish between different colors, especially those with equal luminosity.</p>

    <h3 class="text-center text-xl md:text-xl lg:text-3xl text-violet-400 mt-8 mb-8">Types of Color-Blindness</h3>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">There are several types of color-blindness, the most common being red-green color-blindness. Deuteranopia and Protanopia are two common sub-types of red-green color-blindness. Tritanopia is a blue-yellow color-blindness. In some very rare cases, people inherit an insensitivity to all colors, known as Achromatopsia. <strong>Color alone should never be used to convey important information.</strong></p>

