    <h2 class="font-bold text-center text-xl md:text-3xl lg:text-4xl text-violet-400 mt-32 mb-8">Auditory Disabilities</h2>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">Auditory disabilities include varying degrees of hearing loss, including deafness. People with this type of diability may have difficulty understanding speech and distinguishing background from foreground noise.</p>

    <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">There are several causes of Auditory disabilities including genetics, premature birth, infections/illness, ear trauma, exposre to loud noises and aging. </p>

   <h3 class="text-center text-xl md:text-xl lg:text-3xl text-violet-400 mt-8 mb-8">Deafness vs. Deaf Culture</h3>

   <p class="text-lg/loose md:text-xl/loose lg:text-2xl/loose max-w-prose mb-8">The term "deaf" refers to the condition of being deaf. Deaf with a capital "D" refers to Deaf Culture or Deaf Community. Those in the Deaf Community view deafness from a cultural perspective, using sign language to communicate and belonging to a specific culture. Those in the Deaf Community view deafness using the <a class="underline underline-offset-8 text-violet-400 hover:text-white" href="/posts/social-id-cultural-affiliation">Social Identity or Cultural Affiliation Model of Disability</a>.</p>

